A second alternative is to use GGVSPD or differentiated GGALT as the
slow reference for the integrated acceleration.\footnote{The advantage of using GGALT is that it is present in many past projects
while GGVSPD is a recent addition to the list of variables. Differentiation
of GGALT has verified that, at least at low rate, a result equivalent
to GGVSPD is obtained after an appropriate time shift.} Then a new variable ROCG ($w_{p}^{\prime})$ can be defined as\\
\[
w_{p}^{*}[i]=\sum_{1}^{i}(a_{j}\Delta t)
\]
\begin{equation}
w_{p}^{\prime}=w_{p}^{*}\left(1-F_{s}\right)+F_{s}w_{p}\label{eq:ROCG}
\end{equation}
which shows the complementary-filter nature of the variable. In this
formula, $w_{p}^{*}$ is the result of integrating the acceleration
from the INS (with measurements separated in time by $\Delta t=0.04$~s
for high-rate measurements) and $w_{p}$ is GGVSPD. The function $F_{s}$
is a low-pass filter, taken here as a Butterworth filter with cutoff
period of 10~s. This variable then incorporates the accuracy of GGVSPD
at low frequency with the fast-response of the INS at high frequency.
Like the other complementary filter used for horizontal wind, this
works best if the cutoff period is selected at a point where the signals
are the same so that any phase shift or imprecision at the transition
point is compensated by the combination of identical signals. The
result is a rate-of-climb measurement that does not have the erroneous
3-Hz peak in the variance spectrum.

The next figure shows that this removes the noise peak from WIC. The
red line is the original measurement WIC and the blue line is the
vertical wind recalculated with ROCG as defined by (2).
